Let s \colon  B \to  A and r \colon  A \to  B be a pair of maps. A homotopy h \colon  r\circ  s \sim  1_{B} exhibits s as a section of r and r as a retraction of s. Together, 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen s,r\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 are referred to as a section-retraction pair.

Let \mathcal {A} be a path object, and let B\colon    \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {} \to  \mathsf {Prop} be a family of propositions. Then the reflexive subgraph comprehension 
 \mathopen {}\left \lbrace x:\mathcal {A}\,\middle \vert \,B  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\right \rparen \mathclose {} \right \rbrace \mathclose {}
 is a path object.

