, we employ the covariant sum of each of the pointwise path object structures on \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}-=x over the intrinsic path object structure on A, constructing an identification p\colon  a = a' followed by a homotopy H \colon    \mathopen {}\left \lparen   \mathopen {}\left \lparen \chi _{a'}\right \rparen \mathclose {} _*^{\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}-=x} \chi _\bullet \right \rparen \mathclose {}  \sim  \chi '_\bullet . Fixing z\colon  A, we compute:

Let \epsilon  \colon  f\circ  f^{-1} = 1_{B} be the counit of the inverse to f\colon  A\to  B. Given b:B, we must show that the fiber of f over b is contractible; the centre of contraction is given by the pair 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen f^{-1} x, \epsilon  x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
, and the required paths can be constructed via the univalence principle for fibers using the unit \eta \colon  f^{-1}\circ  f = 1_{A}, the coherence \chi \colon  \mathsf {act}_{f}\circ \eta \sim \epsilon \circ  f, and the naturality of homotopies.

As f is an embedding, the map \mathsf {act}_{f}\colon  a_0 = a_1 \to  fa_0 = fa_1 has an inverse 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \mathsf {act}_{f}^{-1},\epsilon ,\eta ,\chi \right \rparen \mathclose {}
.

Given a function f\colon  A\to  B and a section g\colon  B\to  A witnessed by \epsilon \colon  f\circ  g = 1_{B}, we define the coherent remainder of 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\epsilon \right \rparen \mathclose {}
 to be the following sum:

Given elements 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta _0,\chi _0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 and 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta _1,\chi _1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 of \mathsf {coherentRemainder}_{f}\sigma , the resulting type   \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta _0,\chi _0\right \rparen \mathclose {} \cong _{\mathsf {coherentRemainder}_{f}\sigma }  \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta _1,\chi _1\right \rparen \mathclose {}  is definitionally equivalent to the following dependent sum:

Without loss of generality, we may assume that f has an inverse 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\epsilon ,\eta ,\chi \right \rparen \mathclose {}
. By , it suffices to argue that the type of inverses to f is a retract of a proposition; the type of inverses to f is in fact equivalent to the type of sections equipped with a coherent remainder:

By , it suffices to show that the type of sections to f is a proposition and that for every such section, the coherent remainder thereof is a proposition. The latter is , and the former follows from  by means of the retraction 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\eta \right \rparen \mathclose {}
.
